{"topicId":"runtime-polymorphism-pointers","flashcards":[{"id":"fc-1","front":"What is runtime polymorphism in C++?","back":"Runtime polymorphism allows a base class pointer to invoke the derived class's overridden method at runtime via dynamic dispatch. It is achieved using virtual functions and pointers/references, enabling flexible and extensible code."},{"id":"fc-2","front":"What is a virtual function and how is it declared?","back":"A virtual function is a member function declared in a base class that derived classes can override. Declared using the 'virtual' keyword: `virtual void display();` in base class, then `void display() override;` in derived class."},{"id":"fc-3","front":"What is a vtable (virtual table) in C++?","back":"A vtable is a lookup table used by compilers to implement dynamic dispatch for virtual functions. Each class with virtual functions has its own vtable; objects contain a hidden vptr pointing to their class's vtable."},{"id":"fc-4","front":"What is object slicing in C++?","back":"Object slicing occurs when a derived class object is assigned to a base class object (not pointer), losing its derived parts. Example: `Base b = Derived();` slices off derived portions. Prevent by using pointers or references: `Base* b = &derived;`."},{"id":"fc-5","front":"Why should base class destructors be virtual?","back":"Virtual destructors ensure proper cleanup when a derived object is deleted through a base pointer. Without virtual destructor, only base destructor executes causing memory leaks. Always declare base destructors virtual when inheritance is used."},{"id":"fc-6","front":"What is dynamic binding in C++?","back":"Dynamic binding resolves function calls at runtime based on the actual object type (not pointer type). Occurs only with virtual functions accessed through pointers/references: `Base* ptr = new Derived(); ptr->method(); // calls Derived::method()"`},{"id":"fc-7","front":"What is the output of this code? Base* b = new Derived(); b->show(); Given: Base has virtual show() printing \"Base\" and Derived overrides it printing \"Derived\"","back":"Output: \"Derived\" - The base pointer 'b' points to a Derived object. At runtime, the vtable lookup finds Derived::show() (not Base::show()), demonstrating runtime polymorphism via dynamic dispatch."},{"id":"fc-8","front":"Can virtual functions have static members? Explain.","back":"No, virtual functions cannot be static. Static members belong to class, not objects, so they lack 'this' pointer needed for vtable lookup. Each virtual call requires an object instance to access the correct vtable for dynamic dispatch."}]}